The following code from Paloma's bridge has a race condition. The `pillar_stream` events arrive from the CLI subprocess BEFORE the browser has finished creating the IndexedDB session (triggered by `pillar_session_created` event). This means stream chunks are lost because there's no dbSessionId to route them to yet.

Here's the buggy flow:
```javascript
// In PillarManager.spawn():
this.broadcast({ type: 'pillar_session_created', pillarId, pillar, model })
// CLI subprocess starts immediately and emits stream events
// Browser receives pillar_session_created, creates IndexedDB session (async!)
// Meanwhile, pillar_stream events arrive but pillarSessionMap has no entry yet

// In useMCP.js event handler:
case 'pillar_stream': {
  const dbSessionId = pillarSessionMap.get(event.pillarId)
  if (!dbSessionId) return // LOST DATA — stream arrived before session was created
  appendToSession(dbSessionId, event.text)
  break
}

case 'pillar_session_created': {
  // This is async — creates session in IndexedDB
  const dbId = await createSession(event.pillarId, event.pillar)
  pillarSessionMap.set(event.pillarId, dbId)
  break
}
```

Design and implement a fix using a stream buffer. Requirements:
1. Buffer stream events that arrive before the session is created
2. Flush the buffer once the session IS created
3. Don't buffer forever — if session creation never completes, discard after a timeout
4. Handle the normal case (session created before stream) with zero overhead
